Water soluble green GQDs were purchased from ACS Material, USA. As indicated by the manufacturer, the GQDs had a well-distributed size of <6 nm. The X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS) measurement of the GQDs based on the C1s core level spectra was deconvoluted into four components, namely C-C (sp2), C-C (sp3), C-O, and C=O bonds at 285.0, 286.5, 287.5, and 289.0 eV, respectively [
                        11
                        ]. Cadmium acetate dihydrate (Cd(CH3COO)2·2H2O) was purchased from Hamburg Chemicals, Germany. Thiourea (CH4N2S) was purchased from Fisher Scientific, USA. Chloroauric acid (HAuCl4.3H2O), 3,4-Dihydroxyphenethylamine hydrochloride (DA), and trisodium citrate (Na3C6H5O7) were obtained from Sigma Aldrich, USA. N-butylamine (C4H11N) was purchased from Acros Organics, Belgium. Acetone ((CH3)2CO, 99.5%) was provided by Friendemann Schmidt, USA. Ethanol (CH3CH2OH2, 95%) was purchased from Systerm, Malaysia. Phosphate-buffered saline (PBS), triethanolamine (TEA, 99%), tris(hydroxymethyl)aminomethane, uric acid (UA), glucose (Glu), ascorbic acid (AA), glutathione (GSH), L-cysteine (Cys), glucose (Glu), and other reagents of analytical grade were obtained from Merck, USA. Indium tin oxide (ITO) conducting glass slides (7 Ωsq−1) were commercially supplied by Xin Yan Technology Limited, China. Unless otherwise specified, all materials and reagents were used as received without further purification.

The constructed PEC sensor-based CdS/Au/GQDs photoelectrode was applied for the quantitative determination of various concentrations of DA in a solution containing PBS (pH 9) and TEA at a potential of 0 V vs. Ag/AgCl. As shown in Fig. 4
                     A, the photocurrent responses decreased upon increasing DA concentration. The decrease in photocurrent is mainly attributed to the generation of more BQ groups on the photoelectrode surface, which act as electron acceptors and, thus, induce the recombination of e−-h+ (refer Fig. 1B(ii)). Based on the standard calibration plot of 0.1 to 350 µM DA in Fig. 4B, the linear regression equation of ΔI/μA = 0.0013 C/μM + 0.0464 with a correlation coefficient of 0.9982 was determined. In virtue of the method of signal-to-noise ratio of 3 (S/N = 3), the LoD was calculated to be 0.0078 μM. Compared with other reported DA PEC sensors (Table 1
                     ), the fabricated CdS/Au/GQDs presented in this work exhibits a wider linear range, promising sensitivity, remarkably stability, and enhanced photocurrent signal. A relatively low LoD of DA based on the CdS/Au/GQDs photoelectrode is highly suitable for its use in biomedical applications since the concentration of DA in biological tissues ranges between 0.01 to 1.0 μM [4]. Moreover, our fabricated material exhibits about a 1-fold lower LoD compared to the amount of DA in biological tissue.
